<TITLE> Barua sees no crisis for diverting gas </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, April 1 (bdnews24.com)  The country will not face any crisis due to temporary suspension of gas supply to fertiliser factories, said industry minister Dilip Barua. He made the observation upon conclusion of the first meeting of the national industrial development council on Thursday. Barua said, "The government has a reserve of about five lakh tonnes of urea. The reserve is almost twice more than the corresponding period of last year." The meeting discussed the ruling Awami League's Vision-2021 to turn the country into a middle-income industrial country. It also discussed imperatives of other sub-sectors linked with industries. The meeting, scheduled at the end of the month again, would deal with the formulation of a set of recommendations to speed up industrialisation, a press release said. The meeting also found that, for a balanced socio-economic development, equal opportunities have to be extended to the private sector enterprises along with those in the public sector. The meeting's participants stressed upon an industry-friendly VAT and tax structure to generate employment. Among others, the meeting was also attended by privatisation commission chairman Mirza Abdul Jalil, industry secretary Zakir Hossain and representatives from PMO office, FBCCI, planning commission, BEPZA, Bangladesh Bank and the N
